The surface of silica nanoparticles was coated with an organosilica shell according to the enhanced approach. The dense SiO2 was synthesized with TEOS as the silicon source, and CTAC was employed as a structural template to form mesoporous silica nanoparticles (SiO2@MON). The etching time can be shortened by silicon coating at 80 °C in the presence of CTAC. Generally, the etching time requires > 10 h. By adding a certain concentration of CTAC, the etching time was reduced to 2 h owing to the chemical homology among TEOS, BTES, and organosilicon [32]. Different synthesis conditions influenced the morphological structures [33,34]. 1.8 mL BTES is added to obtain structurally complete SiO2@MON particles. In this process, the reduction of BTES affords the absence of a large number of uniform mesoporous; it may cause the etching agent cannot sufficiently enter the carrier interior to etch the SiO2 core (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). To obtain HMON with a complete outer organosilicon shell structure and large cavity under 80 °C conditions, SiO2@MON was placed in Na2CO3 solution to etch away the core of the SiO2 nanoparticles. The HMON was extracted using NaCl and methanol to remove the template CTAC. In addition, each step of intermediate preparation requires repeated washing with ultrapure water and ethanol to obtain a spherical structure with satisfactory dispersion (Fig. 1
                        ).

The responsive release ability and antifungal effect of the Forsythia–HMON–CQDs system were examined using MIC antifungal assay in vitro. In the control group (Blank), the colony diameter of G. trabeum after culturing for 7 d was 79 mm (Table 1
                        ), and the mycelium growth state showed that the activity of the G. trabeum was outstanding (
                           Fig. S10
                        ). Compared with the control group, various concentrations of Forsythia had a certain inhibitory effect on the growth of G. trabeum, and the antifungal effect was also enhanced with increasing concentration of Forsythia. The MIC of Forsythia was 60 mg/mL. From an antifungal viewpoint, Forsythia was effective as a wood preservative. The growth state of G. trabeum on the medium treated with Forsythia–HMON–CQDs (nature pH value) was similar to that of the blank group. This result demonstrates that the material (nature pH value) has no antifungal effect, and the natural pH value indicates that the Forsythia was not released. This was mainly attributed to the plugging effect of CQDs on mesoporous pores. Compared with the medium treated with Forsythia–HMON–CQDs (nature pH value), the growth of G. trabeum in the medium treated with Forsythia–HMON–CQDs (pH = 4.7) was inhibited (
                           Fig. S11
                        ). This was because the amide bond was broken under appropriate conditions (pH = 4.7), and CQDs were separated from the surface of HMON, affording the exposure of mesoporous pores and the release of Forsythia. The separation process of CQDs has been analyzed in the previous section. MIC antifungal test effectively proved that CQDs can plug the mesoporous. In this process, if CQDs do not exhibit a plugging effect, the Forsythia–HMON–CQDs (nature pH value) will release Forsythia, and inhibit the growth of G. trabeum under the same concentration. However, this is contrary to our fact, which indicates that CQDs plug the mesopores (Table 1). Numerous groups of parallel experiments were performed on the medium supplemented with Forsythia–HMON–CQDs (pH = 4.7). Forsythia was released and played an antifungal role in the growth of G. trabeum. The antifungal effect of Forsythia was more visible with the higher concentration. The comparative analysis revealed that each group could inhibit G. trabeum; however, the inhibitory effect was different (
                           Fig. S10
                        ), and the MIC of Forsythia–HMON–CQDs was 80 mg/mL (Table 1).

SEM and laser confocal microscopy were employed to observe the distribution of Forsythia–HMON–CQDs in wood. The three facets of natural wood were smooth without foreign substances. The cell walls of the treated wood had uniformly distributed nanoparticles, as illustrated by red arrows, indicating that Forsythia–HMON–CQDs were successfully impregnated into the wood. Forsythia–HMON–CQDs can adhere to pits and conduits of wood, indicating that preservative loss can be reduced (
                           Fig. S12
                        ). The fluorescence properties of Forsythia–HMON–CQDs can also be employed to track their distribution in wood (
                           Fig. S6
                        ).
